}\n* Uyghur: {{tt|ug|يا}}\n* Uzbek: {{tt+|uz|yoy}}, {{tt+|uz|kamon}}\n* Vietnamese: {{tt+|vi|cung}} ({{tt+|vi|弓}})\n* Volapük: {{tt+|vo|bob}}\n* Walloon: {{tt+|wa|air|m}}, {{tt+|wa|årbalesse|f}}\n* Welsh: {{tt|cy|bwa|m}}, {{tt|cy|bwâu|m-p}}\n* Yiddish: {{tt|yi|בויגן|m}}\n* Zapotec:\n*: Isthmus Zapotec: {{t-needed|zai}}\n* Zhuang: {{tt|za|gung}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|bend in a rod or planar surface}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|изви́вка|f}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|corba}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|彎曲}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|ohyb|m}}\n* Danish: {{tt|da|bue|c}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|boog|m}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|kaari}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|arc|m}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Bogen|m}}\n*: Bavarian: {{tt|bar|Bogn}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|τόξο|n}}, {{tt+|el|αψίδα|f}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt+|he|קֶשֶׁת|f|tr=késhet}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|bogi|m}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|arco|m}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|свиок|m}}\n* Persian: {{tt+|fa|خَم|tr=xam}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|zgięcie|n}}, {{tt+|pl|zagięcie|n}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|curva|f}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|излу́чина|f}} (of a river), {{tt+|ru|изги́б|m}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{tt|gd|bogha|m}}, {{tt|gd|lùb|f}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt|sh|за́вој|m}}\n*: Latin: {{tt+|sh|závoj|m}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|båge|c}}, {{tt+|sv|krökning|c}}, {{tt+|sv|rundning|c}}\n* Walloon: {{tt+|wa|åtche|f}} {{qualifier|building}}, {{tt+|wa|coube|f}}, {{tt+|wa|tournant|m}} {{qualifier|river}}, {{tt|wa|arondi|m}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|rod used for playing stringed instruments}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Afrikaans: {{tt|af|strykstok}}\n* Arabic: {{t+|ar|قَوْس|m}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{tt|arz|عصاية|f|tr=ʕaṣāya}}\n* Asturian: {{tt|ast|arcu|m}}\n* Belarusian: {{tt|be|смычо́к|m}}, {{tt|be|смык|m}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|gwareg|f}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|лък|m}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|arc}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{tt|cmn|[[弦樂器]]的[[弓]]|tr=xuányuèqì de gōng}}, {{t+|cmn|琴弓|tr=qíngōng}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|smyčec|m}}\n* Danish: {{tt|da|bue|c}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|strijkstok|m}}\n* Esperanto: {{tt+|eo|arĉo}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|jousi}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|archet|m}}\n* Frisian:\n*: West Frisian: {{tt|fy|strykstôk}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Bogen|m}}\n*: Bavarian: {{tt|bar|Bogn}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|δοξάρι|n}}\n* Greenlandic: {{tt|kl|tagiut}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|קֶשֶׁת|f|tr=késhet}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|vonó}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|bogi|m}}\n* Ido: {{t+|io|arketo}}\n* Irish: {{tt|ga|bogha|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|arco|m}}, {{t+|it|archetto|m}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|弓|tr=ゆみ, yumi}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|қияқ}}, {{t|kk|ысқы}}\n* Khmer: {{t+|km|ឆាក}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|활}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{t|ky|смычок}}\n* Latvian: {{tt|lv|lociņš|m}}\n* Lithuanian: {{tt|lt|smičius|m}}, {{tt|lt|strykas|m}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|гудало|n}}\n* Manx: {{tt|gv|bow|m}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|kōpere}}, {{t|mi|whana}}\n* Norman: {{tt|nrf|artchet|m}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t+|nb|bue|m}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{tt|nn|boge|m}}\n* Ojibwe: {{tt|oj|naazhaabike'iganaak}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|آرشِه|tr=ârše}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|smyczek|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|arco|m}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|arcuș|n}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|смычо́к|m}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{tt|gd|bogha|m}}, {{tt|gd|slatag|f}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|гу̀дало|n}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|gùdalo|n}}\n* Slovak: {{tt|sk|sláčik|m}}\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|lok|m}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|arco|m}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|stråke|c}}\n* Thai: {{t+|th|คันชัก}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|yay}}\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|زخمه|tr=zahme}}\n* Ukrainian: {{tt|uk|смичо́к|m}}\n* Uzbek: {{t+|uz|kamoncha}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|vĩ}}\n* Volapük: {{t-needed|vo}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|airçon|m}}\n* Welsh: {{t|cy|bwa|m}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|musical bow}}\n\n{{trans-top-see|type of knot with two loops|bowtie}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Arabic: {{tt|ar|اَنْشُوطَة|f}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{tt|arz|فيونكة|f|tr=feyōnka}}, {{tt|arz|ببيونة|f|tr=bebyōna}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|па́нделка|f}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|llaç|m}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|蝴蝶結|tr=húdiéjié}}\n* Crimean Tatar: {{tt|crh|bağ}}, {{tt|crh|dügüm}} {{qualifier|northern dialect [[bav]]}}\n* Czech: {{tt|cs|klička|f}}\n* Danish: {{tt|da|sløjfe|c}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|strik}}\n* Esperanto: {{tt+|eo|banto}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|rusetti}}, {{tt|fi|nauharuusuke}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Schleife|f}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|φιόγκος|n}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|masni}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt|is|slaufa|f}}\n* Ingrian: {{t|izh|bantta}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|fiocco|m}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|蝶結び|tr=ちょうむすび, chōmusubi}}\n* Korean: {{t|ko|나비매듭}}\n* Latin: {{t-needed|la}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t|lt|kaspinas|m}}, {{t|lt|kaspinėlis}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|панделка|f}}\n* Maltese: {{t|mt|ċoff|m}}\n* Manx: {{tt|gv|kiangle|m}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{tt+|nb|sløyfe|m|f}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{tt|nn|sløyfe|f}}\n* Ojibwe: {{tt|oj|gashka'oojigan}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|kokarda}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|laço|m}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|ба́нтик|m}}, {{tt+|ru|бант|m}}, {{tt+|ru|ба́бочка|f}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt|sh|машна|f}}\n*: Latin: {{tt+|sh|mašna|f}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|lazo|m}}, {{t|es|lacito|m}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|rosett|c}}\n* Thai: {{tt+|th|โบ|tr=boo}}, {{tt|th|โบว์|tr=boo}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|fiyonk}}\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|دوگوم|tr=düğüm}}\n* Walloon: {{tt+|wa|fernuk|m}}\n* Welsh: {{tt|cy|bwa|m}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|anything bent or curved}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|дъга|f}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|torowhiti}} {{qualifier|a curved frame for an awning or tent }}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# To [[play]] music on (a stringed) instrument using a bow.\n#: {{ux|en|The musician '''bowed''' his violin expertly.}}\n# {{lb|en|ergative}} To bend or curve, particularly downward.\n#: {{ux|en|The shelf '''bowed''' under the weight of the books.}}\n#* {{RQ:King James Version|Psalms|62|3|passage=How long wil ye imagine mischiefe against a man? ye shall be slaine all of you: as a '''bowing''' wall shall ye be, and as a tottering fence.}}\n#* {{RQ:Milton Divorce|I|32|{{...}} as when we '''bow''' things the contrary way, to make them come to their naturall ſtraitneſſe.}}\n#* {{RQ:Prescott Mexico|passage=The whole nation {{...}}'''bowed''' their necks to the worst kind of tyranny.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|figurative}} To exercise powerful or controlling influence over; to bend or incline, figuratively; to [[humble]] or [[subdue]].\n#* {{RQ:Bacon Essayes|chapter=Of Atheism|passage=Adversities do more '''bow''' men's minds to religion.}}\n#* {{RQ:Fuller Church History|passage=not to '''bow''' and bias their opinions}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1829|author=w:Edgar Allan Poe|chapter={{w|Tamerlane (poem)|Tamerlane}}|title=Al Aaraaf, Tamerlane and Minor Poems|passage=Know thou the secret of a spirit<br>'''Bow’d''' from its wild pride into shame.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col3|en|bow up|bower|bowable|diddley bower}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|to play music on an instrument using a bow}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Bulgarian: {{t-needed|bg}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{tt|cmn|[[用]][[弓]][[拉]][[曲]]|tr=yòng gōng lā qǔ}}\n* Danish: {{tt+|da|stryge}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|strijken}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|soittaa}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|streichen}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt|is|strjúka}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|弾く|tr=ひく, hiku}}, {{tt+|ja|弾奏|tr=だんそうする, dansou suru|alt=弾奏する}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|гуди}}\n* Polish: {{tt|pl|prowadzić smyczek}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt|pt|[[tocar]] ([[com]] [[arco]])}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to become bent}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Arabic: {{tt|ar|اِنْحَنَى}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt|bg|изви́вам се}}, {{tt|bg|изви́я се}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|corbar|alt=corbar-se}}, {{tt+|ca|doblegar|alt=doblegar-se}}, {{tt+|ca|vinclar|alt=vinclar-se}}, {{tt+|ca|blincar|alt=blincar-se}} {{q|dialectal}}\n* Cherokee: {{tt|chr|ᎠᏗᏍᏚᏍᎦ}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|彎曲|tr=wānqū}}\n* Crimean Tatar: {{tt|crh|qambıraymaq}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|ohnout|alt=ohnout se|pf}}\n* Danish: {{tt|da|bue}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|buigen}}\n* Egyptian: {{t-egy|ksj|h=k-s-A16}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|taipua}}, {{tt+|fi|kaartua}}, {{tt+|fi|vääntyä}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|fléchir}}, {{tt+|fr|courber}}\n* Frisian:\n*: West Frisian: {{tt|fy|bûge}}, {{tt|fy|in bûging meitsjen}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|biegen|alt=sich biegen}}, {{tt+|de|verbiegen|alt=sich verbiegen}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|κυρτώνω}}, {{tt+|el|λυγίζω}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt|he|התכופף|tr=hitkoféf}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|hajlik}}, {{tt+|hu|meghajlik}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt|is|bogna}}, {{tt|is|svigna}}, {{tt|is|bugast}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|curvarsi}}, {{tt+|it|piegarsi}}, {{tt|it|incurvarsi}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|се свиткува}}\n* Manx: {{tt|gv|croym}}\n* Persian: {{tt+|fa|خمیدن|tr=xamidan}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|wygiąć|pf|alt=wygiąć się}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|curvar}}, {{tt+|pt|arquear}}\n* Quechua: {{tt|qu|k'umuy}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|гну́ться|impf}}\n* Scots: {{tt|sco|boo}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{tt|gd|crom}}, {{tt|gd|lùb}}\n* Slovak: {{t-check|sk|ohnúť|alt=ohnúť sa|pf}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|arquear|alt=arquearse}}, {{tt+|es|curvar}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|böja}}, {{tt+|sv|kröka}}, {{tt+|sv|bågna}}, {{tt+|sv|böjas}}, {{tt+|sv|krokna}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to bend a thing}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|изви́вам}}, {{tt+|bg|сви́вам}}, {{tt|bg|изви́я}}, {{tt|bg|сви́я}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|corbar}}, {{tt+|ca|doblegar}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{tt|cmn|弄彎|tr=nòngwān}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|ohnout|pf}}\n* Danish: {{tt+|da|bøje}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|buigen}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|taivuttaa}}, {{tt+|fi|vääntää}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|courber}}\n* Frisian:\n*: West Frisian: {{tt|fy|bûge}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|biegen}}, {{tt+|de|verbiegen}}, {{tt+|de|beugen}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|λυγίζω}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt+|he|כופף|tr=koféf}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|hajlít}}, {{tt+|hu|meghajlít}}, {{tt+|hu|elhajlít}}, {{tt+|hu|behajlít}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|beygja}}, {{tt|is|sveigja}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|curvare}}, {{tt+|it|piegare}}, {{tt+|it|incurvare}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|曲げる|tr=まげる, mageru}}\n* Korean: {{tt+|ko|구부리다}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|свиткува}}\n* Persian: {{tt+|fa|خماندن|tr=xamândan}}, {{tt+|fa|خم کردن|tr=xam kardan}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|zgiąć}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|curvar}}, {{tt+|pt|arquear}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|гнуть|impf}}\n* Scots: {{tt|sco|boo}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{tt|gd|crom}}, {{tt|gd|lùb}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|doblar}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|böja}}, {{tt+|sv|kröka}}\n* Welsh: {{t|cy|bwa|m}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{etymid|en|bend}}\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*bʰewgʰ-}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|bowen}}, {{m|enm|buwen}}, {{m|enm|buȝen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|būgan}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*beugan}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*beuganą}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*bʰewgʰ-|t=to bend}}. \n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|sco|boo}}, {{m|sco|bou|t=to bend, bow}}, {{cog|nl|buigen|t=to bow}}, {{cog|de|biegen|t=to bow}}, {{cog|nds|bugen|t=to bow}}, {{cog|lb|béien|t=to bow}}, {{cog|da|bue|t=to curve, arch}}, {{cog|sv|buga|t=to bow}}, {{cog|got|𐌱𐌹𐌿𐌲𐌰𐌽|t=to bend, bow}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{enPR|bou}}, {{IPA|en|/baʊ/}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-bow-2.ogg|a=UK}}\n** {{audio|en|En-us-bow-2.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{rhymes|en|aʊ|s=1}}\n* {{homophones|en|bao|bough}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To bend oneself as a gesture of respect or deference.\n#* {{RQ:Baum Wizard of Oz|passage=The soldier now blew upon a green whistle, and at once a young girl, dressed in a pretty green silk gown, entered the room. She had lovely green hair and green eyes, and she '''bowed''' low before Dorothy as she said, \"Follow me and I will show you your room.\"}}\n#* {{RQ:Lincoln Pratt's Patients|chapter=4|passage=I told him about everything I could think of; and what I couldn't think of he did. He asked about six questions during my yarn, but every question had a point to it. At the end he '''bowed''' and thanked me once more. As a thanker he was main-truck high; I never see anybody so polite.}}\n#: {{ux|en|That singer always '''bows''' towards her audience for some reason.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|and|intransitive}} To [[debut]].\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1979|author=Bruce Cassiday|title=Dinah!: A Biography|page=115\n|passage=The show '''bowed''' in the first week of December, 1951. Dinah was ready, and so were the technicians who put on her makeup {{...}}}}\n#* '''2010''' (publication date), Kara Krekeler, \"Rebuilding the opera house\", ''West End Word'', volume 39, number 26, December 22, 2010 – January 11, 2011, page 1:\n#*: SCP recently announced that ''How the Grinch Stole Christmas!<!--sic, exclamation point, not colon--> The Musical'' will '''bow''' on the newly renovated stage next December.\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[defer]] (to something).\n#: {{ux|en|I '''bow''' to your better judgement in the matter.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To give a direction, indication, or command to by bowing.\n#* {{RQ:Burroughs Return of Tarzan|version=Burt|page=63|passage=“This way, monsieur,” he said, and led the way up the broad, marble staircase. In another moment he had opened a door, and, drawing aside a heavy curtain, obsequiously '''bowed''' Tarzan into a dimly lighted apartment. Then Jacques vanished.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Agatha Christie|title=Murder on the Orient Express|location=London|publisher=HarperCollins|year=1934|year_published= 2017|chapter=7|page=124|passage=Poirot rose gallantly, '''bowed''' her into the seat opposite him.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1958|year_published=1972|author=w:Anthony Burgess|title=The Enemy in the Blanket|series=The Malayan Trilogy|page=302|passage=He saw himself, in a smart suit and a ''songkok'', '''bowed''' into the opulent suites of Ritzes and Waldorfs and baring, under dark glasses, a hairy chest to a milder sun by a snakeless sea.}}\n\n=====Hypernyms=====\n* {{sense|gesture}} {{l|en|gesture}}; {{l|en|congee}}, {{l|en|congé}}, {{l|en|conge}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col4|en|collapse=n\n|bow down\n|bow down before the porcelain god\n|bow in\n|bowing stone\n|bow out\n|bow to\n|bow and scrape\n|make one's bow\n|scrape and bow\n|take a bow\n|unbow\n|embow|imbow|outbow|overbow|upbow\n}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top-see|to bend oneself as a gesture of respect or deference|kowtow}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|përul}}\n* Arabic: {{tt|ar|اِنْحَنَى لِلتَّحِيَّة|tr=inḥanā li-t-taḥiyya}}, {{tt|ar|اِنْحَنَى}}, {{tt|ar|رَكَعَ}}\n* Aromanian: {{tt|rup|ncljin|alt=mi-ncljin}}\n* Belarusian: {{tt|be|кла́няцца|impf}}, {{tt|be|паклані́цца|pf}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt|bg|покла́ням се|impf}}, {{tt|bg|поклоня́ се|pf}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|corbar}}, {{tt+|ca|doblegar}}, {{tt+|ca|vinclar}}, {{tt+|ca|blincar}} {{q|dialectal}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|鞠躬|tr=jūgōng}}, {{tt+|cmn|躬|tr=gōng}}, {{tt+|cmn|哈腰|tr=hāyāo}}\n* Czech: {{tt|cs|klanět|impf|alt=klanět se}}, {{tt|cs|uklonit|pf|alt=uklonit se}}\n* Danish: {{tt|da|bukke}}, {{tt+|da|bøje|alt=bøje sig}}\n* Dutch: {{tt|nl|[[een]] [[buiging]] [[maken]]}}, {{tt+|nl|buigen|alt=zich buigen}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|riverenci}}, {{tt|eo|kliniĝi}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|kumartaa}}, {{tt+|fi|kumartua}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|s'incliner}}, {{tt|fr|[[faire]] [[une]] [[révérence]]}}\n* Friulian: {{tt|fur|pleâsi}}\n* Galician: {{tt+|gl|agochar}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|verbeugen|alt=sich verbeugen}}, {{tt|de|[[ein|eine]] [[Verbeugung]] [[machen]]}}, {{tt+|de|verneigen|alt=sich verneigen}}\n* Gothic: {{tt|got|𐌰𐌽𐌰𐌷𐌽𐌴𐌹𐍅𐌰𐌽}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|υποκλίνομαι}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt+|he|קד|tr=kad}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|meghajol}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt|is|hneigja sig}}\n* Ingrian: {{t|izh|kummartaa}}\n* Interlingua: {{tt|ia|inclinar se}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|inchinarsi}}, {{tt|it|chinarsi}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|辞儀|tr=じぎする, jigi suru|alt=辞儀する}}, {{tt+|ja|辞儀|tr=おじぎする, o-jigi suru|alt=お辞儀する}}\n* Korean: {{tt+|ko|절하다}}, {{tt|ko|[[절]]을 [[하다]]}}\n* Lakota: {{t|lkt|pathúžA}}\n* Latvian: {{tt|lv|paklanīties}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|се поклонува|impf}}, {{tt|mk|се клања|impf}}\n* Manx: {{tt|gv|croym}}\n* Occitan: {{t|oc|far l'abaissada}}, {{t|oc|s'inclinar}}, {{t|oc|se doblar}}, {{t|oc|se corbar}}\n* Old English: {{t|ang|būgan}}, {{t|ang|hnīgan}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|kłaniać|impf|alt=kłaniać się}}, {{tt+|pl|skłonić|pf|alt=skłonić się}}, {{tt|pl|pokłonić się|pf}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt|pt|[[curvar]]-[[se]]}}, {{t|pt|[[inclinar]]-[[se]]}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|apleca|alt=a se apleca}}, {{tt+|ro|închina|alt=a se închina}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|поклони́ться|pf}}, {{tt+|ru|кла́няться|impf}}\n* Sanskrit: {{tt+|sa|नमति}}\n* Scots: {{tt|sco|boo}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt|sh|клањати|impf|alt=кла̏њати се}}\n*: Latin: {{tt+|sh|klanjati|impf|alt=klȁnjati se}}\n* Slovak: {{tt|sk|klaňať|impf|alt=klaňať sa}}, {{tt|sk|pokloniť|pf|alt=pokloniť sa}}, {{tt|sk|ukláňať|impf|alt=ukláňať sa}}, {{tt|sk|ukloniť|pf|alt=ukloniť sa}}\n* Slovene: {{tt|sl|klanjati se|impf}}, {{tt+|sl|prikloniti se|pf}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|inclinarse}}, {{t+|es|enarcarse}}, {{t+|es|arquearse}}, {{t+|es|prosternarse}}, {{t+|es|debruzar}}, {{t+|es|debruzarse}}, {{t+|es|agobiarse}} {{q|uncommon}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|bocka|alt=bocka (sig)}}, {{tt+|sv|buga|alt=buga (sig)}}\n* Thai: {{tt+|th|โค้ง}}, {{tt+|th|คำนับ}}\n* Turkish:\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|اكمك|tr=eğmek}}\n* Tuvan: {{tt|tyv|мөгейип мендилежир}}\n* Ukrainian: {{tt|uk|кла́нятися|impf}}, {{tt|uk|поклони́тися|pf}}, {{tt|uk|вклони́тися|pf}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|cúi}}, {{t|vi|[[cúi]] [[chào]]}}\n* Welsh: {{t+|cy|ymgrymu}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Breton: {{t+check|br|gwareg|f}} (1)\n* Ido: {{t-check|io|kurv-igar}}\n* Korean: {{t-check|ko|머리를 숙이다}}, {{t-check|ko|허리를 굽히다}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t-check|lt|lankas|m}} (1)\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# A [[gesture]], usually showing [[respect]], made by inclining the head or [[bend]]ing forward at the [[waist]]; a [[reverence]]\n#: {{ux|en|He made a polite '''bow''' as he entered the room.}}\n\n=====Hypernyms=====\n* {{sense|gesture}} {{l|en|gesture}}; {{l|en|congee}}, {{l|en|congé}}, {{l|en|conge}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|gesture made by bending forward at the waist}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Arabic: {{tt|ar|اِنْحِنَاءَة|f}}, {{tt|ar|اِلْتِوَاءَة|f}}\n* Asturian: {{tt|ast|reverencia|f}}\n* Belarusian: {{tt|be|пакло́н|m}}, {{tt|be|укло́н|m}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|покло́н|m}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|reverència|f}}, {{tt+|ca|inclinació|f}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|鞠躬|tr=jūgōng}}\n* Czech: {{tt|cs|poklona|f}}\n* Danish: {{tt|da|buk|n}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|buiging|f}}\n* Erzya: {{tt|myv|сюконявкс}}\n* Esperanto: {{tt|eo|klino}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|kumarrus}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|révérence|f}}\n* Galician: {{tt+|gl|reverencia|f}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Verbeugung|f}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|υπόκλιση|f}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt+|he|קידה|f|tr=kidá}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|नमन|m}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|meghajlás}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|hneiging|f}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|inchino|m}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|辞儀|tr=じぎ, jigi}}, {{tt+|ja|お辞儀|tr=おじぎ, o-jigi}}\n* Korean: {{tt+|ko|절}}\n* Latvian: {{tt|lv|paklanīšanās}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|поклон|m}}\n* Malayalam: {{tt+|ml|കുനിയുക}}\n* Maltese: {{tt|mt|inkin}}\n* Manx: {{tt|gv|croymmey|m}}, {{tt|gv|imlaght|f}}, {{tt|gv|lhoobey|m}}\n* Persian: {{tt+|fa|تعظیم|tr=ta'zim}}, {{tt+|fa|کرنش|tr=korneš}}, {{tt+|fa|نماز|tr=namâz}} {{qualifier|archaic}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|ukłon|m}}, {{tt+|pl|pokłon|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|reverência|f}}, {{tt+|pt|vénia|f}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|покло́н|m}}\n* Sanskrit: {{tt+|sa|नमस्|n}}\n* Scots: {{tt|sco|boo}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{tt|gd|ùmhlachd|f}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt|sh|на́клон|m}}\n*: Latin: {{tt+|sh|náklon|m}}\n* Slovak: {{tt|sk|poklona|f}}\n* Slovene: {{tt+|sl|poklon|m}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|reverencia|f}}, {{t|es|zalema|f}}, {{t+|es|mocha|f}} {{qualifier|with the head}}, {{t+|es|caravana|f}}, {{t|es|prosternación|f}}, {{t+|es|inclinación|f}}, {{t+|es|quiebro|m}}, {{t+|es|agobio|m}}\n* Swedish: {{tt|sv|bockning|c}}, {{tt+|sv|bugning|c}}\n* Thai: {{tt+|th|การโค้ง}}, {{tt+|th|การคำนับ}}\n* Ukrainian: {{tt|uk|поклі́н|m}}, {{tt|uk|уклі́н|m}}\n* Welsh: {{t|cy|ymgrymiad|m}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n{{etymid|en|nautical}}\n{{PIE word|en|bʰeh₂ǵʰús}}\n{{wp|+ (ship)}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|bowe}}, {{m|enm|bowgh}}, a borrowing from {{der|en|gml|bôch}} and/or {{der|en|dum|boech}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*bōguz}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*bʰeh₂ǵʰus||arm}}. {{doublet|en|bough}}.\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|nl|boeg|t=bow}}, {{cog|de|Bug|t=bow, prow (of a ship); shoulder joint (of an animal)}}, {{cog|lb|Buch}}, {{m|lb|Bou|t=shoulder joint (of an animal)}}, {{cog|da|bov|t=bow}}, {{cog|is|bógur|t=bow}}, {{cog|nb|baug|t=bow}}, {{cog|nb|-}}, {{cog|nn|-}} and {{cog|sv|bog|t=bow; shoulder (of an animal)}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{enPR|bou}}, {{IPA|en|/baʊ/}}\n* {{audio|en|en-us-bow-2.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{rhymes|en|aʊ|s=1}}\n* {{homophones|en|bough}}\n\n====Noun====\n[[Image:Bow (PSF).png|thumb|The bow of a ship.]]\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q301897}} {{lb|en|nautical}} The [[front]] of a [[boat]] or [[ship]].\n#: {{syn|en|stem<id:Q301897>|forestem<id:Q301897>|fore<id:Q301897>|prow<id:Q301897>|prore<id:Q301897>}}\n#: {{ant|en|stern<id:Q273062>|aft<id:Q273062>|poop<id:Q273062>}}\n#: {{hol|en|watercraft<id:Q1229765>|<|vessel<id:Q16391167>}}\n#: {{mer|en|beak<id:structural member attached to stem of ship>|beak<id:battering ram portion of ship_s timber>|beakhead<id:battering ram portion of ship_s timber>}}\n#* {{RQ:Bindloss Dust of Conflict|chapter=6|passage=The night was considerably clearer than anybody on board her desired when the schooner ''Ventura'' headed for the land. It rose in places, black and sharp against the velvety indigo, over her dipping '''bow''', though most of the low littoral was wrapped in obscurity.}}\n# {{lb|en|rowing}} The [[rower]] that sits in the [[seat]] closest to the bow of the boat.\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* Often used in the plural, the ship being considered to have [[starboard]] and [[port]] bows, meeting at the [[stem]].\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en\n|bluff-bowed\n|bow ball\n|bow cap\n|bow chaser\n|bow foil\n|bowgrace\n|bowman\n|bowpicker\n|bow plane\n|bow rail\n|bowrider\n|bow riding\n|bow rudder\n|bow shock\n|bowsman\n|bowswoman\n|bow thruster\n|bow wave\n|hurricane bow\n|midbow\n|on the bow\n|overbow\n|ram bow\n|[[shot across the bow]][[shot across the bows|(s)]]\n|weather bow\n}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|front of a boat or ship}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Afrikaans: {{tt+|af|boeg}}\n* Albanian: {{tt+|sq|bash|m}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|قَيْدُوم|m}}\n* Basque: {{tt+|eu|branka}}\n* Belarusian: {{tt|be|нос|m}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|нос|m}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|proa|f}}, {{tt|ca|prora|f}} {{q|Latinism}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|船首}}, {{t+|cmn|船頭}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|příď|f}}\n* Danish: {{tt|da|bov|c}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|boeg|m}}\n* Erzya: {{tt|myv|венчбря}}\n* Esperanto: {{tt+|eo|pruo}}, {{tt|eo|ŝipbeko}}\n* Estonian: {{tt|et|vöör}}, {{tt|et|käil}}\n* Faroese: {{tt|fo|bógvur|m}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|keula}}, {{tt+|fi|kokka}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|proue|f}}\n* Frisian:\n*: West Frisian: {{tt|fy|boech}}\n* Galician: {{tt+|gl|proa|f}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Bug|m}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|πρώρα}}, {{tt+|el|πλώρη}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{tt|grc|πρώρα|f}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|לְחִי הַחַרְטוֹם|m|tr=lekhi hakhartom}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|hajóorr}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|bógur|m}}, {{t|is|stefni|n}}\n* Ido: {{tt+|io|pruo}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|haluan}}\n* Ingrian: {{t|izh|esinukka}}\n* Irish: {{tt|ga|ceann|m}}, {{tt|ga|gob|m}}, {{tt+|ga|srón|f}}, {{tt|ga|tosach|m}}\n* Istriot: {{tt|ist|prùa|f}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|prua|f}}, {{tt+|it|prora|f}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|船首|tr=せんしゅ, senshu}}, {{t+|ja|舳先|tr=へさき, hesaki}}\n* Korean: {{tt+|ko|이물}}, {{tt+|ko|선수(船首)}}\n* Lakota: {{tt|lkt|walpȟá}}\n* Latin: {{tt+|la|rostrum|n}}\n* Latvian: {{tt|lv|priekšgals|m}}\n* Malay: {{tt+|ms|haluan|}}\n* Manx: {{tt|gv|toshiaght|m}}, {{tt|gv|boogh|m}}, {{tt|gv|kione toshee|m}}, {{tt|gv|gob|m}}\n* Māori: {{tt+|mi|ihu}}, {{tt|mi|tauihu}}, {{tt|mi|punake}}, {{tt|mi|puneke}}\n* Nahuatl:\n*: Classical Nahuatl: {{tt|nci|ācalyacatl}}\n* Norman: {{tt|nrf|avant|m}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{tt+|nb|baug|m}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{tt|nn|baug|m}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|سینِه|tr=sine}}\n* Plautdietsch: {{tt|pdt|Bug|f}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|dziób|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|proa|f}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|нос|m}}\n* Scots: {{tt|sco|bou}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{tt|gd|toiseach|m}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt|sh|пра́мац|m}}\n*: Latin: {{tt+|sh|prámac|m}}\n* Slovak: {{tt|sk|prova|f}}, {{t+|sk|čelo|n}}\n* Slovene: {{tt|sl|premec|m}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|proa|f}}\n* Swahili: {{t|sw|gubeti|c5|c6}}, {{t|sw|omo|c5|c6}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|bog|c}}, {{tt+|sv|för|c}}, {{tt+|sv|stäv|c}}\n* Tagalog: {{tt|tl|duong}}, {{tt|tl|doong}}, {{tt|tl|proa}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|pruva}}\n* Ukrainian: {{tt+|uk|ніс|m}}\n* Venetan: {{tt+|vec|pròva|f}}, {{tt|vec|pròda|f}}\n* Welsh: {{tt+|cy|blaen|m}}, {{tt|cy|pen blaen|m}}, {{tt+|cy|trwyn|m}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 4===\nSee {{m|en|bough}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{obsolete spelling of|en|bough}}.\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Tempest|act=V|scene=i|page=17|column=1|passage=Where the Bee ſucks, there ſuck I, / In a Cowſlips bell, I lie, / There I cowch when Owles doe crie, / On the Batts backe I doe flie / after Sommer merrily. / Merrily, merrily, ſhall I liue now / Vnder the bloſſom that hangs on the '''Bow'''.}}\n#* {{RQ:Walton Compleat Angler|chapter=VII|page=154|passage=[Y]ou are to faſten that line to any '''bow''' neer to a hole where a ''Pike'' is, or is likely to lye, or to have a haunt, {{...}}}}\n\n===Etymology 5===\n{{bor+|en|cmn|-}} {{zh-m|包}} or {{bor|en|yue|-}} {{zh-m|包|tr=baau1}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|en|bao|bau}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{C|en|Foods}} {{alternative form of|en|bao}}; any of several Chinese buns and breads\n\n=====Derived terms=====\nSee {{m|en|bao}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-see|bao}}\n\n===Etymology 6===\n{{clipping|en}} of [[en|boutta]], itself a [[Appendix:Glossary#contraction|contraction]] of [[en|about to]].\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{enPR|bou}}, {{IPA|en|/baʊ/}}\n\n* {{audio|en|En-uk-bow-2.ogg|a=UK}}\n\n* {{audio|en|En-us-bow-2.ogg|a=US}}\n\n* {{rhymes|en|aʊ|s=1}}\n\n* {{homophones|en|bough}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|en|verb form}} {{lb|en|auxiliary}} \n\n# [[about to]]\n\n===Etymology 7===\n{{clipping of|en|bow-wow}}\n\n====Interjection====\n{{en-intj}}\n\n# {{ellipsis of|en|bow-wow}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{ellipsis of|en|bow-wow}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{ellipsis of|en|bow-wow}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{l|en|bow chicka wow wow}} {{q|different etymology}}\n* {{l|en|bow diddley}}, {{l|en|diddley bow}} {{q|different etymology}}\n* {{l|en|coll'arco}}<!--musical term-->\n* {{l|en|curtsey}}\n* {{l|en|kowtow}}\n* {{l|en|throw them bows}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{pedia|lang=en|Bow (weapon)}} {{gloss|Wikipedia article on bows (weapons)}}\n* {{pedia|lang=en|Bow (knot)}} {{gloss|Wikipedia article on bows (the knots)}}\n* {{pedia|lang=en|Bowing (social)}} {{gloss|Wikipedia article on bows, the gestures of respect}}\n* {{pedia|lang=en|Bow (ship)}} {{gloss|Wikipedia article on the bows of ships}}\n\n* {{pedia|lang=en|Bow (music)}} {{gloss|Wikipedia article on bows used to play string instruments}}\n* {{pedia|lang=en|Musical bow}} {{gloss|Wikipedia article on musical bows}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Britannica 1911|Bow}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=bow|wbo|Wob|BwO|WBO}}\n\n{{C|en|Body language|Weapons|Ship parts}}\n{{cln|en|heteronyms|3-letter words}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|enm|verb|altform=1}}\n\n# {{tlb|enm|WR}} {{alternative form of|enm|bowen}}\n\n==Sranan Tongo==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{bor|srn|nl|bouwen||to build}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{srn-IPA}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|srn|verb}}\n\n# to [[build]]\n# {{lb|srn|figurative|with {{m|srn|tapu}}}} to [[trust]], to [[depend]] on\n#: {{uxi|srn|wan sma di yu kan '''bow''' na en '''tapu'''|someone you can '''depend on'''}}\n\n==Vilamovian==\n[[File:Jessica Ennis (May 2010) cropped.jpg|180px|thumb|1. '''bow''']]\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|wym|goh|wīb}}, from {{inh|wym|gmw-pro|*wīb}}, from {{inh|wym|gem-pro|*wībą}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|wym|/boːf/}}\n* {{audio|wym|Wym-bow (wersja Józefa Gary).ogg}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{wym-noun|head=bōw|g=f|pl=bowa}}\n\n# [[woman]]\n#: {{syn|wym|fraoj}}\n# [[wife]]\n#: {{syn|wym|fraoj}}\n\n{{C|wym|Family|Female}}\n\n==Yola==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|yol|ga|badhbh}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|yol|/bəʊ/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|yol|noun}}\n\n# [[banshee]]\n# {{lb|yol|derisive}} bad singer\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Muirithe 1990|page=154}}\n\n{{C|yol|People}}"}}